latestPosts.caption:
📸 Creative & Practical Tips… 

	1.	Use Glycerin Spray for controlled wet look without constant water splash.
	2.	Mirror Angles – Check reflections in advance to avoid accidental exposure or unwanted background (especially with crew visible).
	3.	Lighting is Key – Use soft diffused lighting to avoid harsh glares or reflections bouncing back from the mirror.
	4.	Wardrobe Choice – Choose clothes that stick well when wet and won’t become too transparent unless intended. Safety pins help.
	5.	Pose Carefully – Wet shoots can restrict quick movement; hold poses with stability to avoid falls or slips.

latestPosts.caption:
Here are 5 DON’Ts when modeling for Polaroid shots: -

❌ DON’Ts:
	1.	Don’t Over-Pose
Polaroids are meant to be raw and real. Avoid dramatic angles, heavy hand gestures, or editorial poses. Save those for fashion shoots.
	2.	Don’t Wear Distracting Clothes or Accessories
No bold prints, logos, heels (unless requested), or big jewelry. These take the attention away from you.
	3.	Don’t Use Filters or Heavy Editing
Keep the photos unretouched. Agencies will reject overly edited shots.
	4.	Don’t Force Facial Expressions
A calm, neutral face works best. Don’t pout or exaggerate—confidence in simplicity stands out.
	5.	Don’t Use Cluttered Backgrounds
Always shoot against a plain, solid-colored wall (white or light gray is best). No posters, furniture, or mess.
